They are both great I'm 22 and have ADHD, been off my medication for almost 2 years and have been looking for alternatives as I head back into college. I've been trying a variety of these high caffeine coffees, and I intend to give this black label a try, but even brands with a lower dosage give me an adequate buzz. The biohazard brand is around 900mg and for about an hour I feel like I'm on an adderall 10mg. I think my ADHD is a variable in how I experience coffee however as I frequently hear from other people that coffee doesn't have much an effect on them. I've thought about various ways to put what ADHD feels like into words, in terms of integers it feels like this: -1/0/+1 where zero is your mind at homeostasis and -1 is your mind with ADHD. With ADHD your mind is at -1 24/7, a normal person is at 0, and +1 represents high motivation/concentration. A person that is normally at 0 while at rest should have no problem getting to +1 even without taking a stimulus, but for someone that's always at -1, it is much more difficult getting to 0 much less getting to +1. Personally at -1 my thought process feels foggy, and the mental fatigue from various tasks whether it be studying or housework sets in MUCH quicker than it would with someone at 0 or +1, what ends up happening is my mind starts searching for anything even slightly more interesting to focus my attention, sometimes it doesn't even have to be visual, it can be a random thought, and suddenly that single thought takes your mind off on a tangent and you've completely zoned out of whatever you were concentrating on just prior. At 0 or +1 that's technically still possible, but it would take a little longer. The coffee I had brings me to about .25 to .5, so slightly above 0 but not quite 1, however even then I feel much more concentrated and willing to study/work than I am at -1. I wish people could understand the difference between even -1 and 0 is major, if I were approached by a magic genie and told my mind could return to 0 indefinitely at the consequence of never reaching +1, I'd still take that offer, 0 is still much much better than -1. While the game's concept and design are SO incredibly simple, and quite likely just a slight deviation on other existing phone app dungeon crawlers that I've played off and on for years.......it is a masterpiece, no question.  Anything it may have evolved from it has effectively perfected.  Even only being about 5 hrs into gameplay now (and wow, already such a HUGE difference in my skill level) I give this game EASILY an 8.5/10.  Granted, I review it on the basis of its intent and genre: is it gonna have the same level of complexity, graphics, time put in by developers, etc as something like Breath of the Wild?  Obviously not, but it's not trying to be that.  For it's genre, it deserves an 8.5, maybe even 9, out of 10.

I think, in closing, what has to be, by FAR, my favorite element of the game?........you don't directly progress further by just sinking hours into grinding, and you CERTAINLY don't have the option to "pay to win".  No, with "Enter the Gungeon", your success is measured by your skill level -both one's general, meta gaming talents, as well as specific familiarity with this game's mechanics.  There IS no "grind mindlessly" or "burn your $" options to win; if you want to win, you have to BE GOOD.   And that is something SO horrifyingly lost in practically all video games in the modern age: you don't have to demonstrate or gain actual talent or skill to win.
